4:
So, this is the base of the
Kaleidoscope? What an absolute
disaster...
7: Well, boy, do you think you can do it?
11:
To five elements—
Six companions new converge—
Countless paths laid bare.
17:
Magnificent! You're integrating the
six elements of our world into your
own magic. Why, it's enough to send
shivers down my spine!
21:
I call it the Three Thousand
Realms—though I'll admit I only
chose the name because I liked how
it sounded. Do you know what do
now, Couette?
26:
Yes. I can handle it.
Close, Gates of the Abyss...
34:
Hahaha! Absolutely MARVELOUS!
Never would I have thought to
encounter such natural talents!
37:
And you're already passing the fruits
of your knowledge down to the next
generation. You're a glistening gem,
flawless in every way!
46: Couette is a very special girl.
51:
She's very cute and amazing and...
One day, she'll become a powerful
magician.
55:
Y-yes? I do believe I was in the
middle of saying the exact same
thing—
61:
Why didn't you let her into Voluntas
Academy?
65:
Whoa... I had no idea Stella was a
helicopter parent!
69:
Ah... That. Yes, I recall now. I suppose
I did reject the girl's application,
didn't I?
72:
Frankly, I don't see a point in letting
her in. The girl's prodigious talents
will flourish wherever she goes—with
or without instruction.
76: How does THAT make any sense?
81:
But she wanted to go to the
Academy...
86:
Um, S-Stella, you don't need to worry
about me...
91:
Fine, I'll cave! She can be my new
pupil. Is that enough, or would you
like me to give her a diploma right
here and now?
100:
Or... there's always the option of
bringing you under my wing as my
very own daughter...
105:
W-wait a minute! I've got my own
wonderful mom already!
109:
Such a terrible shame... I would have
loved to play parent to an
unparalleled genius like you. What a
thrill that would have been...
115:
Are you just about done faffing
around down there? If so, please get
out of my sight!
119:
...I'll open the path to the exit. Do
whatever you want after that.
123:
He tells us to leave, then HE
disappears. What's got him so
cranky?
127:
How should I know why a sniveling
worm gets himself all tangled? Must
have woken up on the wrong side of
the dirt pile.
130:
Enough of that. How about we
retreat to my home and discuss
your enrollment into the Academy?
133:
And on a more personal note,
there's someone I'm simply dying to
meet—I can hardly contain myself.
138:
That's one hell of a gathering over
there... I half expect some epic battle
to break out.
144:
Marvelous! To think I would actually
lay eyes upon an REAL dragon...
147:
Phew. Get a hold of yourself,
Nihilyana... Ahem. I apologize for
that shameful outburst.
151:
There's something off about this
one, Rams. Perhaps I should freeze
her?
155:
Let's not do that quiet yet, An. Look
at her closely—this woman may just
be the most important person in
that world of hers.
158:
Now, then... What is it you would
know of dragons, mage?
162:
Since the very day we gazed upon
the Dragon's Iris at the bottom of the
Void, we've been captivated by their
very existence...
165:
I wish to delve into the depths of
your entire history. Forgive the
bluntness of the question, but is it
true that you cannot reproduce?
169:
That is indeed true. When one of our
kind faces their end, they are reborn.
Thus do we carry on for eternity.
171:
Moreover, we have no relations by
blood. Ancient dragons cannot be
the ancestors of other dragons.
175:
And yet, the resemblance between
the two "species" is remarkably
uncanny. I would posit that there
MUST exist an ancestor to your kind!
178:
Even the dragons our people knew
of were immensely powerful—take
Enlil, the dragon of the west... Or
Fafnir, who once terrorized our skies.
181:
Yet even they are but distant
descendants of far greater dragons.
186:
According to Gram, dragons existed
long before the first humans.
190:
It's true. The Farlands' history goes
back an entire millennium—as do
legends of the Sheephirds. But those
pale in comparison to the age of
dragons!
192:
Our best estimates suggest they've
been around for at least 12,000
years.
199:
Thinking back on it, Nova told me
that Shibuya is about that age too...
203:
An era of dragons... before even the
Overlords existed? If that's true,
perhaps we should renounce the
title "Ancient Dragons."
206:
We were meant to serve as prey for
the Champion... It is for that reason
alone that the Overlords created us.
208:
I can't deny the possibility that we
are, in the end, nothing but
imitations of regular dragons.
212:
An interesting hypothesis. But what
if precisely the opposite is true?
215:
Humans tend to get themselves
involved in all sorts of risky
situations—a certain annoying gnat
of an ex-husband of mine being a
perfect example.
218:
They leap in without thinking, and as
such often have to find a way to
clean up their mess after the fact—a
way to "control" the risk they took.
223:
You're saying that Ancient Dragons
existed first, then? Are you perhaps
referring to the Origin Dragon?
227:
This time, their means of "control"
was the Champion and
Goddess—though I've yet to
decipher exactly WHY those two
were necessary...
230:
But they did... And perhaps it's
because of that decision that we're
able to gather here today, for this
delightful tea party.
235:
Heh. How about it, An? Shall we
partake? I can't deny the fragrant
aroma is most enticing.
238:
You are an interesting one,
Nihilyana. I would stay a while and
speak with you more.
242:
My goodness—what an HONOR! A
part of me still struggles to believe
this is real... To finally converse with
the object of my fervent obsession!
248:
Nihilyana, are you ever going to
make up with Gram?
254:
G-gah! How could you POSSIBLY th
ink it appropriate to bring up such a
ghastly thought and ruin this
pleasant day?!
258:
Nihilyana and Gram used to be
lovers. After they broke up, Gram
became very depressed.
263:
I see. So we're gossiping about
broken hearts now?
268:
Why not? It's a most intriguing
topic... I'd like to hear the rest of this
story, Nihilyana!
273:
Here I am, sipping tea with actual
DRAGONS... And I'm forced to
engage in such trifling
conversation...
276:
Fine, let's get this over with. Where
should I start this whole miserable
tale?
